 come to know how scientific it is. Even though it was founded in 1796 and its principles n philosophy was written back then But its still coreect till date n much ahead of the time.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Samuel_Hahnemann"}
{"title_page": "List of Antarctic churches", "text_new": "[[File:Trinity Church, Antarctica 7577.JPG|thumb|[[Trinity Church (Antarctica)|Trinity Church]] on [[King George Island (Antarctica)|King George Island]]]]\n[[File:Antarctic-Overview-Map-EN.tif|thumb|Map of the Antarctic]]\n{{Christianity|state=collapsed}}\nThere exist a number of '''Antarctic churches''', including both [[Christianity|Christian]] churches on [[Antarctica]] proper and those that were built south of the [[Antarctic Convergence]]. According to the 6th article of the [[Antarctic Treaty]], Antarctica is defined politically as all land and ice shelves south of the [[60th parallel south|60th parallel]], while the nearest natural boundary is the Antarctic Convergence.\n\nThere are eight churches on Antarctica proper,<ref name=\"PN\">Riedel, Dr. Katja. [https://polar-news.com/antarctic/society/174-faith-in-antarctica-religion-in-the-land-of-eternal-snow Faith in Antarctica \u2013 Religion in the land of eternal snow]. Polar News. April 27, 2016. Retrieved January 18, 2017.</ref>\nwith another two located south of the [[Antarctic Convergence]].<ref name=\"Vice\">Merchant, Brian. [http://motherboard.vice.com/blog/these-are-six-churches-currently-giving-services-to-scientists-on-antarctica Prayer on Ice: The Six Churches Giving Sermons to Scientists on Antarctica] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170103004701/http://motherboard.vice.com/blog/these-are-six-churches-currently-giving-services-to-scientists-on-antarctica |date=2017-01-03 }}. [[Vice (magazine)|Vice]]. March 18, 2013. Retrieves January 2, 2017.</ref> The southernmost of these religious buildings is the [[Chapel of Our Lady of the Snows (Belgrano II Base)|Chapel of Our Lady of the Snows]], a [[Catholic Church|Catholic]] chapel carved out of the ice surrounding the [[Belgrano II Base]], at [[Bertrab Nunatak]].<ref name=\"Churchpop\">[https://churchpop.com/2015/12/30/inside-antarcticas-catholic-ice-chapel-the-worlds-southernmost-church/ Inside Antarctica\u2019s Catholic Ice Chapel, the World\u2019s Southernmost Church]. Church Pop. Retrieved December 29, 2016.</ref> While there are currently only a few freestanding structures dedicated solely to Christian religions, most research stations have small meeting rooms that are dual-purposed partially for religious services. These rooms are also commonly used by adherents of other world religions.<ref name =walk>Gabrielle Walker: ''Antarctica: An Intimate Portrait of a Mysterious Continent'', Houghton Mifflin Harcourt, 2013, {{ISBN|0-15-101520-1}}</ref> The [[Chapel of the Snows]] also hosts services for other faith groups such as [[Latter Day Saints]], [[Baha'i]], and [[Buddhism]].<ref>Chapel of the Snows. ''[http://www.southpolestation.com/trivia/history/chapel.html A history of the Chapel of the Snows]. Retrieved December 29, 2016''</ref> These religious structures serve the entire population of Antarctica, which varies from approximately 4,400 in summer to 1,100 in winter. This population is spread across approximately 40 year-round stations and a range of summer-only stations, camps, and refuges.<ref>[https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/geos/ay.html Antarctica]. [[World Factbook]]. [[CIA]]. February 16, 2016. Retrieved December 29, 2016.</ref>\n\n==Churches==\nThis list catalogs churches and other religious buildings built south of the [[60th parallel south|60th parallel]].\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\"\n!scope=\"col\"| Name\n!scope=\"col\"| Denomination\n!scope=\"col\"| Location \n!scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\"| Year opened\n!scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\"| Picture\n!scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\"| Notes\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| [[Chapel of Our Lady of the Snows (Belgrano II Base)|Chapel of Our Lady of the Snows]]\n| [[Catholic Church|Catholic]]\n| [[Belgrano II Base]], [[Bertrab Nunatak]]\n| After 1979\n| \u2013\n| <ref>[https://churchpop.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/12/via-adventure-network.com_.jpg]</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| [[Chapel of St. Francis of Assisi (Esperanza Base)|San Francisco de Asis Chapel]]\n| [[Catholic Church|Catholic]]\n| [[Esperanza Base]], [[Hope Bay]]\n| 1976\n| \u2013\n| <ref name=\"ncregister\">Stagnaro, Angelo. [http://www.ncregister.com/site/article/antarctica-faith-in-the-land-of-eternal-snows/#view-comments Antarctica: Faith in the Land of Eternal Snows]. [[National Catholic Register]]. February 21, 2016 Retrieved December 29, 2016.</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| [[Chapel of St. Mary Queen of Peace|Chapel of Santa Mar\u00eda Reina de la Paz]]\n| [[Catholic Church|Catholic]]\n| [[Villa Las Estrellas]], [[King George Island (Antarctica)|King George Island]]\n| ?\n| [[File:CAPILLA SANTA MARIA REINA DE LA PAZ.JPG|alt= A white building with a black roof, a small porch, and a double height central tower topped with a white cross|200px]]\n| <ref name=\"ncregister\" />\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| [[Chapel of Santisima Virgen de Lujan, Antarctica|Chapel of Santisima Virgen de Lujan]]\n| [[Catholic Church|Catholic]]\n| [[Marambio Base]], [[Marambio Island]]\n| 1996\n| \u2013\n| <ref>[http://www.marambio.aq/oratoriomarambio.html Oratorio de la Capilla de la Base Marambio]. [[Marambio Base]]. Retrieved December 29, 2016.</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| [[Chapel of the Snows]]\n| [[Non-denominational Christian]]\n| [[McMurdo Station]], [[Ross Island]]\n| 1956<br />\nDestroyed 1978<br />\nRebuilt 1989\n| [[File:Chapel of the Snows.jpg|alt=A low slung white and blue clapboard building with a single central steeple.|200px]]\n| <ref>[http://www.southpolestation.com/trivia/history/chapel.html Chapel of the Snows]. [[Amundsen-Scott South Pole Station]]. Retrieved December 29, 2016.</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| [[St. Ivan Rilski Chapel]]\n| [[Eastern Orthodox Church|Eastern Orthodox]]\n| [[St. Kliment Ohridski Base]], [[Livingston Island]]\n| 2003<br />\nrebuilt 2011\n| [[File:St.-Ivan-Rilski-Chapel-New-Building.jpg|alt=A small red Quonset Hut sittign on a concrete and metal pilings and topped with a cross sits among grey rocks.|200px]]\n| <ref>Ivanov, L. [http://livingston-island.weebly.com/ General Geography and History of Livingston Island.] In: ''Bulgarian Antarctic Research: A Synthesis''. Eds. C. Pimpirev and N. Chipev. Sofia: St. Kliment Ohridski University Press, 2015. pp.&nbsp;17\u201328. {{ISBN|978-954-07-3939-7}}</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| [[St. Volodymyr Chapel]]\n| [[Eastern Orthodox Church|Ukrainian Orthodox]]\n| [[Vernadsky Research Base]], [[Galindez Island]]\n| 2010\u20132011\n| \u2013\n| <ref name=\"PN\" />\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| [[Trinity Church (Antarctica)|Trinity Church]]\n| [[Russian Orthodox Church|Russian Orthodox]]\n| [[King George Island (Antarctica)|King George Island]]\n| 2004\n| [[File:2005-02-25 Trinity Church at Bellingshaussen, Antarctica.jpg|alt=A small but detailed wooden structure built with a front staircase and topped with two onion domes.|200px]]\n| <ref>[http://www.atlasobscura.com/places/trinity-church-on-king-george-island Trinity Church on King George Island]. [[Atlas Obscura]]. Retrieved December 29, 2016.</ref>\n|-\n|}\n\n==Antarctic Churches not on Antarctica==\n\nThis list catalogs churches and other religious buildings built south of the [[Antarctic Convergence]], but north of the [[60th parallel south|60th parallel]].\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\"\n!scope=\"col\"| Name\n!scope=\"col\"| Denomination\n!scope=\"col\"| Location \n!scope=\"col\"| Year opened\n!scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\"| Picture\n!scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\"| Notes\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| [[Norwegian Lutheran Church (Grytviken, South Georgia)|Norwegian Lutheran Church]]<br /> The Whalers Church\n| [[Anglican]]<br/>''<small>formerly [[Church of Norway|Norwegian Lutheran]]</small>''\n| [[Grytviken]], [[South Georgia and the South Sandwich Islands|South Georgia]]\n| 1913\n| [[File:Grytviken church.jpg|alt=A white wooden church nestled within snow-covered mountains.|200px]]\n| <ref>